    "review::.::holistic::mid_level_elegance::session_via_self_http_indirection": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::mid_level_elegance::session_via_self_http_indirection",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 1,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "hooks.server.ts reads the session by self-fetching /auth/session over HTTP instead of calling Auth.js directly",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "mid_level_elegance",
        "related_files": [
          "src/hooks.server.ts",
          "src/auth.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "src/hooks.server.ts handleSession sets event.locals.getSession to a closure that issues `fetch(`${event.url.origin}/auth/session`, { headers: { cookie: event.request.headers.get('cookie') || '' } })` and parses the JSON response",
          "Auth.js (./auth) is already imported at the top of hooks.server.ts as the auth handler, so the session is reachable in-process without crossing the network seam",
          "Every protected handler that calls `await locals.getSession()` (via requireSession) therefore pays a re-entrant HTTP round trip \u2014 re-serialising cookies, re-running middleware, re-parsing JSON \u2014 to obtain data that is already in memory"
        ],
        "suggestion": "Replace the self-fetch in handleSession with a direct call to Auth.js's session helper. With @auth/sveltekit, expose the auth() helper from src/auth.ts and call it from inside the hook (e.g. `event.locals.getSession = () => auth(event)`), or fold the session resolution into the existing handleAuth so locals.session is populated in one pass. Eliminates the HTTP boundary and the cookie hand-off",
        "reasoning": "",
        "summary_hash": "eb211d6a"
      },
      "status": "fixed",
      "note": "not reported in latest holistic re-import",
      "first_seen": "2026-04-26T14:29:22+00:00",
