      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 1,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "Authenticated POST handlers skip request-body validation that public POST siblings apply, splitting the trust boundary",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "authorization_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "src/routes/api/current-state/+server.ts",
          "src/routes/api/recent-characters/+server.ts",
          "src/routes/api/recent-reports/+server.ts",
          "src/routes/api/death-events/+server.ts",
          "src/routes/api/fights/+server.ts",
          "src/routes/api/player-details/+server.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "current-state/+server.ts:50 \u2014 `const { urlParams }: Omit<CurrentState, 'timestamp'> = await request.json();` \u2014 no try/catch around parse, no shape check; a non-JSON or malformed body throws an unhandled SyntaxError that the surrounding try/catch then logs as a generic 'save failed'.",
          "recent-characters/+server.ts:40 \u2014 `const { characterName, realm, region } = await request.json();` \u2014 values flow straight into addUserRecent without any type/length checks; characterName is also interpolated into the entity key `${characterName}-${realm}` (line 43).",
          "recent-reports/+server.ts:45 \u2014 `const { code, title, guild, owner } = await request.json();` \u2014 same shape, no validation.",
          "Public siblings consistently use the safer pattern: death-events/+server.ts:66 `const body = parseFightRequestBody(await request.json().catch(() => null));`, fights/+server.ts:38 `const body = (await request.json().catch(() => null)) as { code?: unknown } | null;`, player-details/+server.ts:26 same pattern."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Add a tiny shared helper in src/lib/server/ (e.g., `parseJsonBody<T>(request, validate): Promise<T | Response>`) that wraps `request.json().catch(() => null)` and returns apiError('Invalid request body', 400) on failure, then thread it through the three authenticated POST handlers (current-state, recent-characters, recent-reports). This matches what the public sibling endpoints already do and makes the trust boundary symmetric without introducing a new validation framework.",
