    "review::.::holistic::logic_clarity::char_reports_duplicate_fallback_query": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::logic_clarity::char_reports_duplicate_fallback_query",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 1,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "fetchReportsForGuild loops over two byte-identical GraphQL queries, and its catch returns [] inside the loop, so the fallback path is dead",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "logic_clarity",
        "related_files": [
          "src/routes/api/character-reports/+server.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "GUILD_RECENT_REPORTS_QUERY and GUILD_REPORTS_QUERY have the same operation, same selection set, same `limit: 8`, same arguments \u2014 they differ only in the `query` operation name.",
          "`for (const query of queries)` iterates [identical1, identical2]; on success it returns; on catch it `return []` (not `continue`), so the second iteration can never execute and would return the same data anyway."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Delete GUILD_REPORTS_QUERY (it is a duplicate of GUILD_RECENT_REPORTS_QUERY) and inline the single query into fetchReportsForGuild without a loop. If a real fallback was intended (e.g., a different filter window), define a second query that actually differs and change the catch from `return []` to `continue` so the loop can fall through to the next attempt.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "summary_hash": "8032cd5c"
